SIMPLE: incoherency
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incoherency
<hw>In`co*her"en*cy</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>incoh⟦eacute⟧rence</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being incoherent; lack of
coherence; lack of cohesion or adherence.</def>
<rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Lack of connection; incongruity; inconsistency; lack
of agreement or dependence of one part on another; <as>as, the
<ex>incoherence</ex> of arguments, facts, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Incoherences</qex> in matter, and suppositions without
proofs, put handsomely together, are apt to pass for strong reason.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is incoherent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Crude <qex>incoherencies</qex> . . . and nauseous tautologies.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incoherent</ent>⟦br⟧
